Honey seeker depicted on 8000 year old <a href="/wiki/Cave_painting" title="Cave painting">cave painting</a> near <a href="/wiki/Valencia,_Spain" title="Valencia, Spain">Valencia, Spain</a><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Beekeeping</b> (or <b>apiculture</b>, from <a href="/wiki/Latin" title="Latin">Latin</a> <i><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/apis" class="extiw" title="wiktionary:apis">apis</a></i>, <a href="/wiki/Bee" title="Bee">bee</a>) is the maintenance of <a href="/wiki/Honey_bee" title="Honey bee">honey bee</a> colonies, commonly in <a href="/wiki/Beehive" title="Beehive">hives</a>, by humans. A <a href="/wiki/Beekeeper" title="Beekeeper">beekeeper</a> (or apiarist) keeps bees in order to collect <a href="/wiki/Honey" title="Honey">honey</a> and <a href="/wiki/Beeswax" title="Beeswax">beeswax</a>, for the purpose of <a href="/wiki/Pollination" title="Pollination">pollinating</a> <a href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">crops</a>, or to produce bees for sale to other beekeepers. A location where bees are kept is called an <a href="/wiki/Apiary" title="Apiary">apiary</a>.</p>
